2 SENATE BILL 895
1 Section 2–801 through 2–803 to be under the new subtitle “Subtitle 8. School
2 Mapping Data Program”
3 Annotated Code of Maryland
4 (2022 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
5 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
6 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
7 Article – Education
8 [5–310.1.
9 (a) The Interagency Commission shall adopt facility mapping standards for the
10 uniform mapping of the physical attributes of public schools in the State.
11 (b) Local school systems shall:
12 (1) Cooperate with the Interagency Commission in the development of
13 uniform mapping standards; and
14 (2) Contribute data as requested by the Interagency Commission.]
15 [7–1510.1.
16 (a) (1) In this section the following words have the meanings indicated.
17 (2) “Program” means the School Mapping Data Program.
18 (3) “School mapping data” means data in an electronic or digital format to
19 assist first responders in responding to emergencies at a school.
20 (b) There is a School Mapping Data Program in the Center.
21 (c) The purpose of the Program is to provide funds to local school systems to
22 produce school mapping data for each public school in the county, including public charter
23 schools.
24 (d) (1) Each local school system, in consultation with the local law enforcement
25 agency, may apply to the Subcabinet for funds to produce school mapping data.
26 (2) School mapping data produced with funding from the Program shall
27 comply with the facility mapping standards developed by the Interagency Commission on
28 School Construction under § 5–310.1 of this article.
29 (3) The Center shall work in consultation with the Interagency
30 Commission on School Construction to ensure that school mapping data produced with

SENATE BILL 895 3
1 funding from the Program meets the facility mapping standards developed under § 5–310.1
2 of this article.
3 (4) At a minimum, school mapping data produced with funding from the
4 Program shall:
5 (i) Be compatible with software platforms used by the school and
6 local, State, and federal public safety agencies that provide emergency services to the school
7 without requiring the purchase of additional software or charging a fee to view or access
8 the data;
9 (ii) Be in a printable format and, if requested, be in a digital file
10 format that can be integrated into interactive mobile platforms;
11 (iii) Be verified for accuracy by a walk–through of the school
12 buildings and grounds;
13 (iv) Be oriented true north;
14 (v) Be overlaid on current aerial imagery;
15 (vi) Contain site–specific labeling that matches the structure of
16 school buildings, including:
17 1. Room labels;
18 2. Hallway names;
19 3. External door or stairwell numbers; and
20 4. Locations of:
21 A. Hazards;
22 B. Critical utility locations;
23 C. Key boxes; and
24 D. Automated external defibrillators and trauma kits;
25 (vii) Contain site–specific labeling that matches the school grounds,
26 including:
27 1. Parking areas;
28 2. Athletic fields;

4 SENATE BILL 895
1 3. Surrounding roads; and
2 4. Neighboring properties; and
3 (viii) Be overlaid with gridded x and y coordinates.]
4 7–1512.
5 (a) There is a Safe Schools Fund.
6 (b) The purpose of the Fund is to provide grants to local school systems to enhance
7 school safety.
8 (c) The Subcabinet shall administer the Fund.
9 (f) Except as provided in subsections (g) and (h) of this section, the Fund may be
10 used only to provide grants to local school systems to enhance school safety, including:
11 (1) Conducting training for students and school personnel on de–escalation
12 of situations and identifying and reporting behaviors of concern;
13 (2) Conducting training of assessment teams;
14 (3) Conducting school safety evaluations;
15 (4) Establishing formal and anonymous mechanisms for reporting safety
16 concerns;
17 (5) Reimbursing local law enforcement agencies for school resource officer
18 training provided by the Center;
19 (6) Enrolling school security employees in training provided by the Center;
20 (7) Developing plans to deliver school–based behavioral health and other
21 wraparound services to students who exhibit behaviors of concern, including establishing
22 systems to maximize external funding for services;
23 (8) Outreach to the broader school community to improve school safety,
24 including to heighten awareness of existing mental health services and other services;
25 (9) Providing information to students and parents on traveling safely to
26 and from school, including data related to bus and pedestrian safety, strategies for ensuring
27 personal safety, efforts of the local school system to improve safety, and information on
28 available options for reporting incidents and concerns; and

SENATE BILL 895 5
1 (10) Assisting local school systems to improve and monitor traffic control
2 measures in the immediate vicinity of schools to reduce the potential for pedestrian and
3 vehicle accidents.
4 (h) The Subcabinet may use the Fund to provide funding to [local school systems]
5 PUBLIC SAFETY AGENCIES in accordance with [§ 7–1510.1 of this subtitle] TITLE 2,
6 SUBTITLE 8 OF THE PUBLIC SAFETY ARTICLE.
7 Article – Public Safety
8 SUBTITLE 8. SCHOOL MAPPING DATA PROGRAM.
9 2–801.
10 (A) IN THIS SUBTITLE THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
11 INDICATED.
12 (B) “PROGRAM” MEANS THE SCHOOL MAPPING DATA PROGRAM.
13 (C) “PUBLIC SAFETY AGENCY” MEANS A STATE, COUNTY, MUNICIPAL, OR
14 REGIONAL AGENCY THAT PROVIDES FIRE FIGHTING, LAW ENFORCEMENT, MEDICAL,
15 AND OTHER EMERGENCY SERVICES.
16 (D) (1) “SCHOOL MAPPING DATA” MEANS DETAILED AND VERIFIED
17 GEOGRAPHICAL AND STRUCTURAL DATA OF SCHOOL BUILDINGS AND GROUNDS TO
18 ASSIST PUBLIC SAFETY AGENCIES IN RESPONDING TO EMERGENCIES AT A SCHOOL.
19 (2) “SCHOOL MAPPING DATA” INCLUDES:
20 (I) FLOOR PLANS;
21 (II) AERIAL IMAGERY; AND
22 (III) SITE–SPECIFIC LABELS IDENTIFYING ROOMS, HALLWAYS,
23 AND STAIRWELLS.
24 (E) “SOFTWARE PLATFORM” MEANS DIGITAL TOOLS AND SYSTEMS A
25 PUBLIC SAFETY AGENCY USES TO ACCESS, SHARE, AND USE SCHOOL MAPPING DATA
26 AND RELATED EMERGENCY INFORMATION.
27 (F) “VERIFIED DATA” MEANS DATA PHYSICALLY INSPECTED AND
28 CONFIRMED FOR ACCURACY BY AN ON–SITE REVIEW OF SCHOOL BUILDINGS AND
29 GROUNDS BY AN ENTITY RESPONSIBLE FOR PRODUCING SCHOOL MAPPING DATA.

6 SENATE BILL 895
1 2–802.
2 (A) THERE IS A SCHOOL MAPPING DATA PROGRAM IN THE DEPARTMENT.
3 (B) THE PURPOSE OF THE PROGRAM IS TO PROVIDE OVERSIGHT OF, AND
4 TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE TO, PUBLIC SAFETY AGENCIES THAT RECEIVE FUNDS FROM
5 THE SAFE SCHOOLS FUND TO PRODUCE SCHOOL MAPPING DATA FOR EACH PUBLIC
6 SCHOOL IN A COUNTY, INCLUDING PUBLIC CHARTER SCHOOLS, TO FACILITATE
7 EFFICIENT AND EFFECTIVE EMERGENCY RESPONSE BY PUBLIC SAFETY AGENCIES.
8 (C) THE PROGRAM SHALL ENSURE THAT SCHOOL MAPPING DATA
9 PRODUCED BY A PUBLIC SAFETY AGENCY MEETS OR EXCEEDS SCHOOL MAPPING
10 DATA STANDARDS ESTABLISHED AND UPDATED BY THE INTERAGENCY COMMISSION
11 ON SCHOOL CONSTRUCTION.
12 2–803.
13 (A) EACH LOCAL PUBLIC SAFETY AGENCY MAY APPLY TO THE SCHOOL
14 SAFETY SUBCABINET UNDER § 7–1512 OF THE EDUCATION ARTICLE FOR FUNDS TO
15 PRODUCE SCHOOL MAPPING DATA OF A LOCAL PUBLIC SCHOOL OVER WHICH THE
16 PUBLIC SAFETY AGENCY HAS JURISDICTION.
17 (B) A LOCAL PUBLIC SAFETY AGENCY, IN CONSULTATION WITH THE
18 PROGRAM, SHALL ENSURE THAT SCHOOL MAPPING DATA MEETS STANDARDS
19 ESTABLISHED IN SUBSECTION (C) OF THIS SECTION.
20 (C) AT A MINIMUM, SCHOOL MAPPING DATA PRODUCED BY A PUBLIC
21 SAFETY AGENCY WITH FUNDING FROM THE SAFE SCHOOLS FUND SHALL:
22 (1) BE COMPATIBLE WITH SOFTWARE PLATFORMS USED BY THE
23 SCHOOL AND LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL PUBLIC SAFETY AGENCIES THAT
24 PROVIDE EMERGENCY SERVICES TO THE SCHOOL WITHOUT REQUIRING THE
25 PURCHASE OF ADDITIONAL SOFTWARE OR CHARGING A FEE TO VIEW OR ACCESS THE
26 DATA;
27 (2) BE IN A PRINTABLE FORMAT AND, IF REQUESTED, BE IN A DIGITAL
28 FILE FORMAT THAT CAN BE INTEGRATED INTO INTERACTIVE MOBILE PLATFORMS;
29 (3) BE VERIFIED FOR ACCURACY BY A WALK–THROUGH OF THE
30 SCHOOL BUILDINGS AND GROUNDS;
31 (4) BE ORIENTED TRUE NORTH;
32 (5) BE OVERLAID ON CURRENT AERIAL IMAGERY;

SENATE BILL 895 7
1 (6) CONTAIN SITE–SPECIFIC LABELING THAT MATCHES THE
2 STRUCTURE OF SCHOOL BUILDINGS, INCLUDING:
3 (I) ROOM LABELS;
4 (II) HALLWAY NAMES;
5 (III) EXTERNAL DOOR OR STAIRWELL NUMBERS; AND
6 (IV) LOCATIONS OF:
7 1. HAZARDS;
8 2. CRITICAL UTILITY LOCATIONS;
9 3. KEY BOXES; AND
10 4. AUTOMATED EXTERNAL DEFIBRILLATORS AND
11 TRAUMA KITS;
12 (7) CONTAIN SITE–SPECIFIC LABELING THAT MATCHES THE SCHOOL
13 GROUNDS, INCLUDING:
14 (I) PARKING AREAS;
15 (II) ATHLETIC FIELDS;
16 (III) SURROUNDING ROADS; AND
17 (IV) NEIGHBORING PROPERTIES; AND
18 (8) BE OVERLAID WITH GRIDDED X AND Y COORDINATES.
19 (D) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL ADOPT REGULATIONS TO CARRY OUT THIS
20 SUBTITLE.
21 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
22 October 1, 2026.

